1
00:00:33,200 --> 00:00:36,100
<i>The world is changed.</i>

2
00:00:36,400 --> 00:00:39,300
<i>I feel it in the water.</i>

3
00:00:40,200 --> 00:00:42,900
<i>I feel it in the earth.</i>

4
00:00:44,700 --> 00:00:47,500
<i>I smell it in the air.</i>

5
00:00:48,100 --> 00:00:49,900
<i>Much that once was...</i>

6
00:00:50,200 --> 00:00:51,600
<i>...is lost.</i>

7
00:00:52,400 --> 00:00:55,300
<i>For none now live who remember it.</i>

8
00:01:08,400 --> 00:01:12,600
<i>It began with the forging</i>
<i>of the Great Rings.</i>

9
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:14,800
<i>Three were given to the Elves:</i>

10
00:01:15,100 --> 00:01:18,700
<i>Immortal, wisest and fairest</i>
<i>of all beings.</i>

11
00:01:19,900 --> 00:01:21,900
<i>Seven to the Dwarf-lords:</i>

12
00:01:22,800 --> 00:01:27,000
<i>Great miners and craftsmen</i>
<i>of the mountain halls.</i>

13
00:01:27,600 --> 00:01:28,800
<i>And nine...</i>

14
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:31,900
<i>...nine rings were gifted</i>
<i>to the race of Men...</i>

15
00:01:32,300 --> 00:01:36,000
<i>...who, above all else, desire power.</i>

16
00:01:37,300 --> 00:01:42,300
<i>For within these rings was bound</i>
<i>the strength and will to govern each race.</i>

17
00:01:43,900 --> 00:01:46,900
<i>But they were all of them deceived.</i>

18
00:01:47,400 --> 00:01:49,400
<i>For another ring was made.</i>

19
00:01:50,300 --> 00:01:53,700
<i>In the land of Mordor,</i>
<i>in the fires of Mount Doom...</i>

20
00:01:54,300 --> 00:01:58,600
<i>...the Dark Lord Sauron forged</i>
<i>in secret a Master Ring...</i>

21
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:01,000
<i>...to control all others.</i>

22
00:02:01,200 --> 00:02:05,000
<i>And into this Ring he poured</i>
<i>his cruelty, his malice...</i>

23
00:02:05,400 --> 00:02:09,400
<i>...and his will to dominate all life.</i>

24
00:02:10,500 --> 00:02:14,200
<i>One Ring to rule them all.</i>

25
00:02:15,300 --> 00:02:16,800
<i>One by one...</i>

26
00:02:17,200 --> 00:02:21,600
<i>...the Free Lands of Middle-earth</i>
<i>fell to the power of the Ring.</i>

27
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:24,900
<i>But there were some who resisted.</i>

28
00:02:25,500 --> 00:02:30,000
<i>A Last Alliance of Men and Elves</i>
<i>marched against the armies of Mordor.</i>

29
00:02:30,400 --> 00:02:34,800
<i>And on the slopes of Mount Doom, they</i>
<i>fought for the freedom of Middle-earth.</i>

30
00:03:05,400 --> 00:03:07,900
<i>Victory was near.</i>

31
00:03:12,800 --> 00:03:14,400
<i>But the power of the Ring...</i>

32
00:03:15,400 --> 00:03:16,700
<i>...could not be undone.</i>

33
00:03:41,300 --> 00:03:43,100
<i>It was in this moment...</i>

34
00:03:43,500 --> 00:03:45,700
<i>...when all hope had faded...</i>

35
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:50,000
<i>...that Isildur, son of the king,</i>
<i>took up his father's sword.</i>

36
00:04:21,300 --> 00:04:27,500
<i>Sauron, the enemy of the Free Peoples</i>
<i>of Middle-earth, was defeated.</i>

37
00:04:34,600 --> 00:04:36,700
<i>The Ring passed to Isildur...</i>

38
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:41,000
<i>...who had this one chance</i>
<i>to destroy evil forever.</i>

39
00:04:41,900 --> 00:04:44,000
<i>But the hearts of Men...</i>

40
00:04:44,300 --> 00:04:46,700
<i>...are easily corrupted.</i>

41
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:51,400
<i>And the Ring of Power</i>
<i>has a will of its own.</i>

42
00:05:16,800 --> 00:05:19,300
<i>It betrayed Isildur...</i>

43
00:05:21,300 --> 00:05:23,600
<i>...to his death.</i>

44
00:05:27,900 --> 00:05:31,600
<i>And some things</i>
<i>that should not have been forgotten...</i>

45
00:05:31,900 --> 00:05:34,200
<i>...were lost.</i>

46
00:05:35,200 --> 00:05:37,300
<i>History became legend...</i>

47
00:05:37,600 --> 00:05:39,500
<i>...legend became myth.</i>

48
00:05:39,800 --> 00:05:42,500
<i>And for</i>
<i>two and a half thousand years...</i>

49
00:05:42,800 --> 00:05:46,400
<i>...the Ring passed</i>
<i>out of all knowledge.</i>

50
00:05:47,200 --> 00:05:49,900
<i>Until, when chance came...</i>

51
00:05:50,700 --> 00:05:53,600
<i>...it ensnared a new bearer.</i>

52
00:05:55,100 --> 00:05:59,800
My precious.

53
00:06:00,200 --> 00:06:02,600
<i>The Ring came to the creature</i>
<i>Gollum...</i>

54
00:06:02,900 --> 00:06:06,700
<i>...who took it deep into the tunnels</i>
<i>of the Misty Mountains.</i>

55
00:06:07,200 --> 00:06:09,900
<i>And there it consumed him.</i>

56
00:06:10,200 --> 00:06:12,200
It came to me.

57
00:06:12,500 --> 00:06:16,700
My own. My love. My own.

58
00:06:17,100 --> 00:06:21,600
My precious.

59
00:06:25,400 --> 00:06:28,700
<i>The Ring brought to Gollum</i>
<i>unnatural long life.</i>

60
00:06:29,100 --> 00:06:32,800
<i>For 500 years it poisoned his mind.</i>

61
00:06:33,100 --> 00:06:37,500
<i>And in the gloom of Gollum's cave,</i>
<i>it waited.</i>

62
00:06:37,900 --> 00:06:41,000
<i>Darkness crept back</i>
<i>into the forests of the world.</i>

63
00:06:41,400 --> 00:06:44,100
<i>Rumor grew of a shadow in the East...</i>

64
00:06:44,500 --> 00:06:47,100
<i>...whispers of a nameless fear.</i>

65
00:06:47,400 --> 00:06:50,600
<i>And the Ring of Power perceived...</i>

66
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:53,700
<i>...its time had now come.</i>

67
00:06:56,200 --> 00:06:58,800
<i>It abandoned Gollum.</i>

68
00:06:59,500 --> 00:07:03,800
<i>But something happened then</i>
<i>the Ring did not intend.</i>

69
00:07:04,800 --> 00:07:09,200
<i>It was picked up by the most unlikely</i>
<i>creature imaginable.</i>

70
00:07:09,600 --> 00:07:10,600
What's this?

71
00:07:10,900 --> 00:07:12,300
<i>A Hobbit.</i>

72
00:07:12,600 --> 00:07:15,200
<i>Bilbo Baggins of the Shire.</i>

73
00:07:15,500 --> 00:07:17,200
A ring.

74
00:07:17,500 --> 00:07:19,300
Lost!

75
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:25,300
My precious is lost!

76
00:07:25,800 --> 00:07:27,900
<i>For the time will soon come...</i>

77
00:07:28,300 --> 00:07:33,200
<i>...when Hobbits will shape</i>
<i>the fortunes of all.</i>

78
00:07:38,200 --> 00:07:41,100
The 22nd day of September...

79
00:07:41,400 --> 00:07:44,500
...in the year 1400...

80
00:07:44,900 --> 00:07:47,100
...by Shire-reckoning.

81
00:07:47,400 --> 00:07:52,900
Bag End, Bagshot Row, Hobbiton,
Westfarthing...

82
00:07:53,300 --> 00:07:55,200
...the Shire...

83
00:07:55,500 --> 00:07:58,200
...Middle-earth.

84
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:06,200
The Third Age of this world.

85
00:08:17,900 --> 00:08:21,700
<i>There and Back Again:</i>

86
00:08:22,400 --> 00:08:24,100
<i>A Hobbit's Tale.</i>

87
00:08:24,400 --> 00:08:28,200
By Bilbo Baggins.

88
00:08:33,100 --> 00:08:34,800
Now...

89
00:08:35,600 --> 00:08:37,500
...where to begin?

90
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:39,900
Ah, yes...

91
00:08:44,400 --> 00:08:46,200
"Concerning...

92
00:08:47,400 --> 00:08:48,900
...Hobbits."

93
00:08:50,100 --> 00:08:53,500
<i>Hobbits have been living and farming</i>
<i>in the four Farthings of the Shire...</i>

94
00:08:53,900 --> 00:08:55,700
<i>...for many hundreds of years...</i>

95
00:08:56,100 --> 00:08:58,900
<i>...quite content to ignore</i>
<i>and be ignored...</i>

96
00:08:59,200 --> 00:09:02,200
<i>...by the world of the Big Folk.</i>

97
00:09:02,800 --> 00:09:08,100
<i>Middle-earth being, after all,</i>
<i>full of strange creatures beyond count...</i>

98
00:09:08,600 --> 00:09:11,600
<i>...Hobbits must seem</i>
<i>of little importance...</i>

99
00:09:11,900 --> 00:09:15,700
<i>...being neither renowned</i>
<i>as great warriors...</i>

100
00:09:16,100 --> 00:09:20,100
<i>...nor counted among the very wise.</i>

101
00:09:24,600 --> 00:09:27,500
Frodo! Someone at the door.

102
00:09:28,900 --> 00:09:31,300
<i>In fact, it has been remarked by some...</i>

103
00:09:31,600 --> 00:09:35,800
<i>...that Hobbits' only real passion</i>
<i>is for food.</i>

104
00:09:36,400 --> 00:09:38,500
<i>A rather unfair observation...</i>

105
00:09:38,800 --> 00:09:42,300
<i>...as we have also developed a keen</i>
<i>interest in the brewing of ales...</i>

106
00:09:42,900 --> 00:09:45,500
<i>...and the smoking of pipe-weed.</i>

107
00:09:46,100 --> 00:09:48,800
<i>But where our hearts truly lie...</i>

108
00:09:49,100 --> 00:09:51,100
<i>...is in peace and quiet...</i>

109
00:09:52,000 --> 00:09:54,100
<i>...and good, tilled earth.</i>

110
00:09:54,400 --> 00:09:59,300
<i>For all Hobbits share a love</i>
<i>of things that grow.</i>

111
00:10:02,700 --> 00:10:06,800
<i>And, yes, no doubt to others,</i>
<i>our ways seem quaint.</i>

112
00:10:07,200 --> 00:10:12,300
<i>But today of all days,</i>
<i>it is brought home to me:</i>

113
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:18,700
<i>It is no bad thing</i>
<i>to celebrate a simple life.</i>

114
00:10:23,100 --> 00:10:26,200
Frodo, the door!

115
00:10:30,200 --> 00:10:32,000
Sticklebacks. Where is that boy?

116
00:10:32,300 --> 00:10:33,900
Frodo!

117
00:10:39,800 --> 00:10:43,200
<i>Down from the door where it began</i>

118
00:10:48,100 --> 00:10:51,800
<i>And I must follow if I can</i>

119
00:10:52,900 --> 00:10:56,900
<i>The road goes ever on and on</i>

120
00:10:57,200 --> 00:11:00,500
<i>Down from the door where it began</i>

121
00:11:00,900 --> 00:11:05,700
<i>Now far ahead the road has gone</i>

122
00:11:06,500 --> 00:11:10,100
- <i>And I must follow if I can</i>
- You're late.

123
00:11:13,600 --> 00:11:17,200
A wizard is never late, Frodo Baggins.

124
00:11:18,200 --> 00:11:22,600
Nor is he early. He arrives
precisely when he means to.

125
00:11:34,100 --> 00:11:37,000
It's wonderful to see you, Gandalf!

126
00:11:41,100 --> 00:11:44,600
You didn't think I'd miss
your Uncle Bilbo's birthday?

127
00:11:46,500 --> 00:11:48,500
How is the old rascal?

128
00:11:49,100 --> 00:11:52,500
I hear it's going to be a party
of special magnificence.

129
00:11:52,900 --> 00:11:55,200
You know Bilbo.
He's got the whole place in an uproar.

130
00:11:55,500 --> 00:11:57,300
Well, that should please him.

131
00:11:57,700 --> 00:11:59,400
Half the Shire's been invited.

132
00:11:59,800 --> 00:12:02,300
And the rest of them are turning up
anyway.

133
00:12:05,600 --> 00:12:08,700
<i>And so life in the Shire goes</i> on...

134
00:12:09,100 --> 00:12:12,000
<i>...very much as it has</i>
<i>this past Age...</i>

135
00:12:12,300 --> 00:12:17,600
<i>...full of its own comings and goings,</i>
<i>with change coming slowly.</i>

136
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:19,800
<i>If it comes at all.</i>

137
00:12:21,200 --> 00:12:24,500
<i>For things are made to endure</i>
<i>in the Shire...</i>

138
00:12:24,800 --> 00:12:28,100
<i>...passing from one generation</i>
<i>to the next.</i>

139
00:12:28,800 --> 00:12:33,500
<i>There's always been a Baggins</i>
<i>living here under the Hill...</i>

140
00:12:33,900 --> 00:12:35,200
<i>...in Bag End.</i>

141
00:12:37,900 --> 00:12:40,600
And there always will be.

142
00:12:41,500 --> 00:12:44,800
To tell you the truth,
Bilbo's been a bit odd lately.

143
00:12:46,200 --> 00:12:48,300
I mean, more than usual.

144
00:12:49,400 --> 00:12:51,200
He's taken to locking himself
in his study.

145
00:12:52,800 --> 00:12:56,800
<i>He spends hours poring over old maps</i>
<i>when he thinks I'm not looking.</i>

146
00:13:09,700 --> 00:13:11,300
Where's it gone?

147
00:13:38,100 --> 00:13:40,200
He's up to something.

148
00:13:48,400 --> 00:13:50,800
- All right, then. Keep your secrets.
- What?

149
00:13:51,100 --> 00:13:52,800
But I know you have something
to do with it.

150
00:13:53,100 --> 00:13:54,100
Good gracious me.

151
00:13:54,700 --> 00:13:57,300
Before you came along, we Bagginses
were very well thought of.

152
00:13:57,600 --> 00:13:58,500
Indeed.

153
00:13:58,800 --> 00:14:00,900
Never had any adventures
or did anything unexpected.

154
00:14:01,600 --> 00:14:07,300
If you're referring to the incident
with the dragon, I was barely involved.

155
00:14:07,700 --> 00:14:11,100
All I did was give your uncle
a little nudge out of the door.

156
00:14:11,500 --> 00:14:15,400
Whatever you did, you've been officially
labeled a disturber of the peace.

157
00:14:15,900 --> 00:14:17,700
Oh, really?

158
00:14:23,600 --> 00:14:25,400
Gandalf! Gandalf!

159
00:14:31,600 --> 00:14:32,800
Fireworks, Gandalf!

160
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:38,500
- Gandalf!
- Fireworks, Gandalf!

161
00:14:57,400 --> 00:14:58,300
Gandalf?

162
00:14:59,000 --> 00:15:02,900
- I'm glad you're back.
- So am I, dear boy.

163
00:15:07,500 --> 00:15:09,200
So am I.

164
00:15:41,200 --> 00:15:42,500
No, thank you!

165
00:15:42,800 --> 00:15:46,600
We don't want any more visitors,
well-wishers or distant relations!

166
00:15:47,000 --> 00:15:50,400
And what about very old friends?

167
00:15:53,600 --> 00:15:55,200
Gandalf?

168
00:15:56,000 --> 00:15:59,300
- Bilbo Baggins.
- My dear Gandalf!

169
00:15:59,700 --> 00:16:04,600
Good to see you. 111 years old!
Who would believe it?

170
00:16:06,600 --> 00:16:08,500
You haven't aged a day.

171
00:16:15,200 --> 00:16:17,100
Come on, come in!

172
00:16:17,400 --> 00:16:19,700
Welcome, welcome.

173
00:16:20,900 --> 00:16:23,300
Oh, here we are.

174
00:16:25,200 --> 00:16:27,500
Tea? Or maybe something
a little stronger?

175
00:16:27,800 --> 00:16:31,400
I've got a few bottles
of the Old Winyard left. 1296.

176
00:16:31,800 --> 00:16:35,700
Very good year. Almost as old as I am.

177
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:41,300
It was laid down by my father.
What say we open one, eh?

178
00:16:41,700 --> 00:16:44,300
Just tea, thank you.

179
00:16:50,800 --> 00:16:52,400
I was expecting you sometime
last week.

180
00:16:52,600 --> 00:16:55,700
Not that it matters. You come and go as
you please. Always have and always will.

181
00:16:56,100 --> 00:17:01,100
You caught me a bit unprepared. We've only
got cold chicken and a bit of pickle...

182
00:17:01,500 --> 00:17:04,800
There's some cheese here.
No, that won't do.

183
00:17:05,200 --> 00:17:08,900
We've got raspberry jam,
an apple tart...

184
00:17:09,700 --> 00:17:13,500
But not much for afters.
Oh, no, we're all right.

185
00:17:13,900 --> 00:17:16,600
I've just found some sponge cake.

186
00:17:19,600 --> 00:17:20,900
I could make you some eggs
if you'd...

187
00:17:24,900 --> 00:17:27,400
- just tea, thank you.
- Oh, right.

188
00:17:28,600 --> 00:17:30,800
- You don't mind if I eat, do you?
- No, not at all.

189
00:17:31,900 --> 00:17:33,700
Bilbo! Bilbo Baggins!

190
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:35,500
I'm not at home!

191
00:17:41,600 --> 00:17:44,100
It's the Sackville-Bagginses.

192
00:17:44,500 --> 00:17:46,500
- I know you're in there!
- They're after the house.

193
00:17:47,200 --> 00:17:49,600
They've never forgiven me
for living this long.

194
00:17:49,900 --> 00:17:52,600
I've got to get away from these confounded
relatives, hanging on the bell all day...

195
00:17:52,900 --> 00:17:54,700
...never giving me a moment's peace.

196
00:17:55,500 --> 00:17:58,900
I want to see mountains again.
Mountains, Gandalf!

197
00:17:59,300 --> 00:18:03,600
And then find somewhere quiet
where I can finish my book. Oh, tea.

198
00:18:04,100 --> 00:18:07,800
- So you mean to go through with your plan?
- Yes, yes. It's all in hand.

199
00:18:08,100 --> 00:18:10,300
All the arrangements are made.

200
00:18:12,500 --> 00:18:13,900
Oh, thank you.

201
00:18:14,700 --> 00:18:16,700
Frodo suspects something.

202
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:19,400
Of course he does. He's a Baggins...

203
00:18:19,700 --> 00:18:22,200
...not some blockheaded Bracegirdle
from Hardbottle.

204
00:18:22,800 --> 00:18:25,500
You will tell him, won't you?

205
00:18:26,600 --> 00:18:28,500
- Yes, yes.
- He's very fond of you.

206
00:18:30,700 --> 00:18:32,200
I know.

207
00:18:34,600 --> 00:18:37,900
He'd probably come with me
if I asked him.

208
00:18:38,700 --> 00:18:42,000
I think in his heart, Frodo's
still in love with the Shire.

209
00:18:43,700 --> 00:18:45,900
The woods, the fields.

210
00:18:46,200 --> 00:18:48,400
Little rivers.

211
00:18:53,000 --> 00:18:55,600
I am old, Gandalf.

212
00:18:57,000 --> 00:19:02,100
I know I don't look it, but I'm
beginning to feel it in my heart.

213
00:19:04,500 --> 00:19:06,800
I feel thin.

214
00:19:07,200 --> 00:19:08,800
Sort of stretched...

215
00:19:10,200 --> 00:19:13,400
...like butter scraped
over too much bread.

216
00:19:13,700 --> 00:19:18,000
I need a holiday. A very long holiday.

217
00:19:18,400 --> 00:19:21,500
And I don't expect I shall return.

218
00:19:23,800 --> 00:19:26,900
In fact, I mean not to.

219
00:19:29,800 --> 00:19:33,700
Old Toby. The finest weed
in the Southfarthing.

220
00:19:51,100 --> 00:19:53,500
Gandalf, my old friend...

221
00:19:53,900 --> 00:19:56,600
...this will be a night to remember.

222
00:20:19,600 --> 00:20:20,600
Hello, hello.

223
00:20:20,800 --> 00:20:24,700
Fatty Bolger. Lovely to see you.
Welcome, welcome.

224
00:20:25,900 --> 00:20:28,300
Go on, Sam. Ask Rosie for a dance.

225
00:20:31,200 --> 00:20:34,600
- I think I'll just have another ale.
- Oh, no, you don't.

226
00:20:35,700 --> 00:20:37,400
Go on!

227
00:20:47,600 --> 00:20:49,400
So there I was...

228
00:20:49,700 --> 00:20:53,500
...at the mercy
of three monstrous trolls.

229
00:20:54,000 --> 00:20:55,900
And they were all arguing
amongst themselves...

230
00:20:56,200 --> 00:20:58,400
...about how they were
going to cook us.

231
00:20:58,800 --> 00:21:03,600
Whether it be turned on a spit, or to sit
on us one by one, squash us into jelly.

232
00:21:04,800 --> 00:21:08,100
They spent so much time arguing
the whithertos and the whyfors...

233
00:21:08,600 --> 00:21:12,000
...that the sun's first light
crept over the top of the trees...

234
00:21:13,200 --> 00:21:15,500
...and turned them all to stone!

235
00:21:20,900 --> 00:21:22,200
Quickly.

236
00:21:26,500 --> 00:21:28,400
Up they go!

237
00:21:31,400 --> 00:21:32,500
No, the big one.

238
00:21:41,700 --> 00:21:44,400
Mrs. Bracegirdle, how nice to see you.
Welcome, welcome.

239
00:21:44,900 --> 00:21:46,600
Are all these children yours?

240
00:21:47,000 --> 00:21:49,800
Good gracious,
you have been productive.

241
00:21:52,000 --> 00:21:53,200
Bilbo?

242
00:21:55,000 --> 00:21:56,600
Sackville-Bagginses!

243
00:21:56,900 --> 00:21:57,900
Quickly, hide!

244
00:22:07,800 --> 00:22:09,900
Thank you, my boy.

245
00:22:11,600 --> 00:22:13,800
You're a good lad, Frodo.

246
00:22:15,100 --> 00:22:17,800
I'm very selfish, you know.

247
00:22:18,400 --> 00:22:21,700
Yes, I am. Very selfish.

248
00:22:22,200 --> 00:22:24,300
I don't know why I took you in
after your mother and father died...

249
00:22:24,600 --> 00:22:26,000
...but it wasn't out of charity.

250
00:22:26,700 --> 00:22:28,000
I think it was because...

251
00:22:28,200 --> 00:22:30,500
...of all my numerous relations...

252
00:22:31,000 --> 00:22:34,300
...you were the one Baggins
that showed real spirit.

253
00:22:34,700 --> 00:22:36,400
Bilbo, have you been
at the Gaffer's home brew?

254
00:22:36,800 --> 00:22:38,300
No.

255
00:22:38,700 --> 00:22:41,200
Well, yes, but that's not the point.

256
00:22:41,500 --> 00:22:44,700
The point is, Frodo...

257
00:22:47,800 --> 00:22:49,700
...you'll be all right.

258
00:22:53,300 --> 00:22:55,200
- Done!
- You're supposed to stick it in the ground.

259
00:22:55,600 --> 00:22:56,900
- It is in the ground.
- Outside!

260
00:22:57,200 --> 00:22:58,600
This was your idea.

261
00:23:14,500 --> 00:23:16,000
Bilbo.

262
00:23:17,200 --> 00:23:19,900
Bilbo, watch out for the dragon!

263
00:23:20,300 --> 00:23:23,500
Nonsense. There hasn't been a dragon
in these parts for a thousand years.

264
00:23:37,100 --> 00:23:40,600
- That was good.
- Let's get another one.

265
00:23:42,100 --> 00:23:46,400
Meriadoc Brandybuck and Peregrin Took.

266
00:23:46,700 --> 00:23:48,500
I might've known.

267
00:23:54,500 --> 00:23:56,500
Speech, Bilbo!

268
00:23:57,500 --> 00:23:58,700
Speech!

269
00:23:58,900 --> 00:23:59,900
Speech!

270
00:24:05,200 --> 00:24:07,400
My dear Bagginses and Boffins...

271
00:24:08,300 --> 00:24:10,300
...Tooks and Brandybucks...

272
00:24:10,600 --> 00:24:13,000
...Grubbs, Chubbs...

273
00:24:13,300 --> 00:24:14,300
...Hornblowers...

274
00:24:15,600 --> 00:24:17,100
...Bolgers...

275
00:24:17,600 --> 00:24:19,100
...Bracegirdles...

276
00:24:19,400 --> 00:24:21,900
...and Proudfoots.
- Proudfeet!

277
00:24:24,200 --> 00:24:27,200
Today is my 111th birthday!

278
00:24:29,200 --> 00:24:30,600
Happy birthday!

279
00:24:30,800 --> 00:24:34,900
But alas, eleventy-one years is
far too short a time to live among...

280
00:24:35,300 --> 00:24:38,100
...such excellent
and admirable Hobbits.

281
00:24:39,200 --> 00:24:41,800
I don't know half of you
half as well as I should like...

282
00:24:42,100 --> 00:24:46,500
...and I like less than half of you
half as well as you deserve.

283
00:24:56,700 --> 00:24:59,000
I have things to do.

284
00:25:05,500 --> 00:25:07,500
I've put this off far too long.

285
00:25:11,400 --> 00:25:15,200
I regret to announce this is the end!

286
00:25:16,500 --> 00:25:17,600
I'm going now.

287
00:25:18,800 --> 00:25:21,600
I bid you all a very fond farewell.

288
00:25:24,100 --> 00:25:25,200
Goodbye.

289
00:25:58,500 --> 00:26:01,500
I suppose you think
that was terribly clever.

290
00:26:01,900 --> 00:26:05,100
Come on, Gandalf.
Did you see their faces?

291
00:26:05,400 --> 00:26:10,200
There are many magic rings in this world,
and none of them should be used lightly.

292
00:26:10,700 --> 00:26:12,700
It was just a bit of fun.

293
00:26:13,000 --> 00:26:16,600
Oh, you're probably right, as usual.

294
00:26:18,100 --> 00:26:21,500
- You will keep an eye on Frodo, won't you?
- Two eyes.

295
00:26:21,900 --> 00:26:24,500
As often as I can spare them.

296
00:26:24,800 --> 00:26:27,800
- I'm leaving everything to him.
- What about this ring of yours?

297
00:26:28,100 --> 00:26:31,300
- Is that staying too?
- Yes, yes.

298
00:26:32,100 --> 00:26:35,800
It's in an envelope over there
on the mantelpiece.

299
00:26:37,100 --> 00:26:39,900
No. Wait, it's...

300
00:26:42,500 --> 00:26:45,100
...here in my pocket.

301
00:26:49,700 --> 00:26:52,900
Isn't that...? Isn't that odd, now?

302
00:26:54,700 --> 00:26:58,100
Yet, after all, why not?

303
00:26:59,800 --> 00:27:04,400
- Why shouldn't I keep it?
- I think you should leave the ring behind.

304
00:27:05,100 --> 00:27:07,100
Is that so hard?

305
00:27:07,400 --> 00:27:08,700
Well, no.

306
00:27:11,200 --> 00:27:12,700
And yes.

307
00:27:14,700 --> 00:27:17,600
Now it comes to it,
I don't feel like parting with it.

308
00:27:18,000 --> 00:27:19,700
It's mine. I found it! It came to me!

309
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:24,000
- There's no need to get angry.
- Well, if I'm angry, it's your fault!

310
00:27:24,600 --> 00:27:26,300
It's mine.

311
00:27:27,700 --> 00:27:30,100
My own.

312
00:27:30,500 --> 00:27:34,300
- My precious.
- Precious?

313
00:27:34,700 --> 00:27:37,500
It's been called that before,
but not by you.

314
00:27:37,800 --> 00:27:40,200
What business is it of yours
what I do with my own things?

315
00:27:40,600 --> 00:27:43,200
I think you've had that ring
quite long enough.

316
00:27:43,500 --> 00:27:46,200
- You want it for yourself!
- Bilbo Baggins!

317
00:27:46,500 --> 00:27:50,600
Do not take me for some conjurer
of cheap tricks.

318
00:27:51,000 --> 00:27:54,500
I am not trying to rob you.

319
00:27:59,700 --> 00:28:01,300
I'm trying to help you.

320
00:28:09,900 --> 00:28:13,100
All your long years,
we've been friends.

321
00:28:13,600 --> 00:28:15,600
Trust me as you once did.

322
00:28:17,600 --> 00:28:19,400
Let it go.

323
00:28:20,500 --> 00:28:22,900
You're right, Gandalf.

324
00:28:25,100 --> 00:28:27,700
The ring must go to Frodo.

325
00:28:29,200 --> 00:28:32,000
It's late. The road is long.

326
00:28:32,300 --> 00:28:34,700
Yes, it is time.

327
00:28:37,500 --> 00:28:42,400
Bilbo, the ring is still in your pocket.

328
00:29:17,300 --> 00:29:20,200
I've thought up an ending for my book:

329
00:29:21,900 --> 00:29:26,700
"And he lived happily ever after
to the end of his days."

330
00:29:27,100 --> 00:29:30,400
And I'm sure you will, my dear friend.

331
00:29:31,600 --> 00:29:33,000
Goodbye, Gandalf.

332
00:29:35,600 --> 00:29:38,400
Goodbye, dear Bilbo.

333
00:29:46,300 --> 00:29:50,300
<i>The road goes ever on and on</i>

334
00:29:53,100 --> 00:29:55,400
Until our next meeting.

335
00:30:22,800 --> 00:30:26,300
<i>It's mine. My own.</i>

336
00:30:26,700 --> 00:30:30,000
<i>My precious.</i>

337
00:30:30,300 --> 00:30:33,100
Riddles in the dark.

338
00:30:33,500 --> 00:30:34,900
Bilbo!

339
00:30:35,100 --> 00:30:36,600
Bilbo!

340
00:30:40,300 --> 00:30:43,100
My precious.

341
00:30:44,800 --> 00:30:46,900
Precious.

342
00:30:47,200 --> 00:30:49,700
He's gone, hasn't he?

343
00:30:52,500 --> 00:30:55,500
He talked for so long about leaving...

344
00:30:55,900 --> 00:30:58,500
...I didn't think he'd really do it.

345
00:31:03,100 --> 00:31:04,900
Gandalf?

346
00:31:13,200 --> 00:31:14,800
Bilbo's ring.

347
00:31:15,200 --> 00:31:17,500
He's gone to stay with the Elves.

348
00:31:17,800 --> 00:31:20,800
He's left you Bag End.

349
00:31:24,500 --> 00:31:26,800
Along with all his possessions.

350
00:31:27,200 --> 00:31:29,900
The ring is yours now.

351
00:31:32,700 --> 00:31:36,000
- Put it somewhere out of sight.
- Where are you going?

352
00:31:36,400 --> 00:31:38,500
- There are some things that I must see to.
- What things?

353
00:31:38,800 --> 00:31:42,900
- Questions. Questions that need answering.
- You've only just arrived.

354
00:31:44,000 --> 00:31:46,500
I don't understand.

355
00:31:50,000 --> 00:31:50,900
Neither do I.

356
00:31:54,200 --> 00:31:56,400
Keep it secret.

357
00:31:56,800 --> 00:31:58,500
Keep it safe.

358
00:32:33,600 --> 00:32:35,600
<i>Shire!</i>

359
00:32:36,000 --> 00:32:39,000
<i>Baggins!</i>

360
00:33:27,700 --> 00:33:30,500
<i>"The year 3434 of the Second Age.</i>

361
00:33:30,800 --> 00:33:35,000
<i>Here follows the account of Isildur,</i>
<i>High King of Gondor...</i>

362
00:33:35,400 --> 00:33:38,900
<i>...and the finding</i>
<i>of the Ring of Power. "

363
00:33:42,600 --> 00:33:44,300
<i>"It has come to me.</i>

364
00:33:44,600 --> 00:33:47,900
<i>The One Ring. It shall be</i>
<i>an heirloom of my kingdom.</i>

365
00:33:48,200 --> 00:33:51,500
<i>All those who follow in my bloodline</i>
<i>shall be bound to its fate...</i>

366
00:33:51,900 --> 00:33:55,500
<i>...for I will risk</i>
<i>no hurt to the Ring.</i>

367
00:33:55,900 --> 00:33:58,200
<i>It is precious to</i> me...

368
00:33:59,300 --> 00:34:01,800
<i>...though I buy it with great pain.</i>

369
00:34:05,000 --> 00:34:09,000
<i>The markings upon the band</i>
<i>begin to fade.</i>

370
00:34:09,600 --> 00:34:14,100
<i>The writing, which at first was as clear</i>
<i>as red flame, has all but disappeared.</i>

371
00:34:14,500 --> 00:34:18,400
<i>A secret now</i>
<i>that only fire can tell. "

372
00:34:35,000 --> 00:34:37,800
Shire.

373
00:34:38,200 --> 00:34:40,100
Baggins.

374
00:34:40,700 --> 00:34:44,500
There's no Bagginses around here.
They're all up in Hobbiton.

375
00:34:46,500 --> 00:34:47,900
That way.

376
00:34:54,000 --> 00:34:56,000
<i>To heal my heart and drown my woe</i>

377
00:34:56,400 --> 00:34:58,500
<i>Rain may fall and wind may blow</i>

378
00:34:58,900 --> 00:35:00,700
<i>But there still be</i>

379
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:02,300
<i>Many miles to go</i>

380
00:35:02,600 --> 00:35:04,400
<i>Sweet is the sound of the pouring rain</i>

381
00:35:04,700 --> 00:35:06,800
<i>And the stream that falls</i>
<i>From hill to plain</i>

382
00:35:07,100 --> 00:35:08,800
<i>Better than rain or rippling brook</i>

383
00:35:09,100 --> 00:35:11,400
<i>Is a mug of beer inside this Took</i>

384
00:35:14,900 --> 00:35:17,600
There's been some strange folk
crossing the Shire.

385
00:35:18,300 --> 00:35:21,900
Dwarves and others of a less
than savory nature.

386
00:35:22,600 --> 00:35:23,900
War is brewing.

387
00:35:24,600 --> 00:35:27,300
The mountains are fair teeming
with goblins.

388
00:35:27,700 --> 00:35:30,200
Far-off tales and children's stories,
that's all that is.

389
00:35:30,500 --> 00:35:34,800
You're beginning to sound like that old
Bilbo Baggins. Cracked, he was.

390
00:35:35,200 --> 00:35:38,000
Young Mr. Frodo here,
he's cracking.

391
00:35:38,300 --> 00:35:39,600
And proud of it.

392
00:35:40,000 --> 00:35:42,100
- Cheers, Gaffer.
- Cheers.

393
00:35:42,400 --> 00:35:46,300
It's none of our concern what goes on
beyond our borders.

394
00:35:46,600 --> 00:35:50,700
Keep your nose out of trouble,
and no trouble'll come to you.

395
00:35:54,400 --> 00:35:56,500
- Good night, lads.
- Good night.

396
00:35:56,700 --> 00:36:00,900
Good night, sweet maiden
of the golden ale.

397
00:36:01,400 --> 00:36:03,600
Mind who you're sweet-talking.

398
00:36:03,900 --> 00:36:08,200
Don't worry, Sam. Rosie knows an idiot
when she sees one.

399
00:36:09,500 --> 00:36:10,700
Does she?

400
00:36:11,300 --> 00:36:14,200
- Good night, Sam.
- Good night, Mister Frodo.

401
00:36:39,100 --> 00:36:41,500
Is it secret? Is it safe?

402
00:36:50,400 --> 00:36:52,500
What are you doing?

403
00:37:05,200 --> 00:37:07,600
Hold out your hand, Frodo.

404
00:37:08,000 --> 00:37:09,100
It's quite cool.

405
00:37:12,600 --> 00:37:14,300
What can you see?

406
00:37:16,200 --> 00:37:18,500
Can you see anything?

407
00:37:21,300 --> 00:37:22,600
Nothing.

408
00:37:23,400 --> 00:37:25,300
There's nothing.

409
00:37:26,400 --> 00:37:27,800
Wait.

410
00:37:32,000 --> 00:37:34,100
There are markings.

411
00:37:35,700 --> 00:37:39,000
It's some form of Elvish.
I can't read it.

412
00:37:39,300 --> 00:37:41,800
There are few who can.

413
00:37:42,500 --> 00:37:47,100
The language is that of Mordor,
which I will not utter here.

414
00:37:48,000 --> 00:37:48,900
Mordor!

415
00:37:49,200 --> 00:37:51,100
In the common tongue, it says:

416
00:37:51,500 --> 00:37:54,800
"One Ring to rule them all...

417
00:37:55,200 --> 00:37:57,400
...One Ring to find them...

418
00:37:57,800 --> 00:37:59,900
...One Ring to bring them all...

419
00:38:00,200 --> 00:38:03,100
...and in the darkness bind them."

420
00:38:04,900 --> 00:38:06,800
This is the One Ring...

421
00:38:07,200 --> 00:38:12,200
...forged by the Dark Lord Sauron
in the fires of Mount Doom.

422
00:38:12,600 --> 00:38:16,500
Taken by Isildur
from the hand of Sauron himself.

423
00:38:17,400 --> 00:38:19,900
Bilbo found it.

424
00:38:20,400 --> 00:38:22,200
- In Gollum's cave.
- Yes.

425
00:38:22,600 --> 00:38:26,900
For 60 years, the Ring lay quiet
in Bilbo's keeping...

426
00:38:27,300 --> 00:38:30,500
...prolonging his life,
delaying old age.

427
00:38:31,400 --> 00:38:35,600
But no longer, Frodo.
Evil is stirring in Mordor.

428
00:38:35,900 --> 00:38:38,200
The Ring has awoken.

429
00:38:38,600 --> 00:38:41,200
It's heard its master's call.

430
00:38:41,600 --> 00:38:45,300
But he was destroyed.
Sauron was destroyed.

431
00:38:51,200 --> 00:38:53,100
No, Frodo.

432
00:38:54,200 --> 00:38:57,300
The spirit of Sauron endured.

433
00:38:57,600 --> 00:39:02,800
His life force is bound to the Ring,
and the Ring survived.

434
00:39:03,300 --> 00:39:05,400
Sauron has returned.

435
00:39:06,400 --> 00:39:08,400
His Orcs have multiplied.

436
00:39:08,700 --> 00:39:12,500
His fortress at Barad-dr
is rebuilt in the land of Mordor.

437
00:39:12,900 --> 00:39:17,500
Sauron needs only this Ring to cover
all the lands in a second darkness.

438
00:39:17,900 --> 00:39:19,900
He is seeking it.

439
00:39:20,200 --> 00:39:23,900
Seeking it. All his thought
is bent on it.

440
00:39:24,200 --> 00:39:26,800
For the Ring yearns above all else...

441
00:39:27,100 --> 00:39:30,400
...to return to the hand
of its master.

442
00:39:30,800 --> 00:39:32,500
They are one...

443
00:39:32,800 --> 00:39:35,700
...the Ring and the Dark Lord.

444
00:39:36,000 --> 00:39:37,000
Frodo...

445
00:39:37,700 --> 00:39:39,400
...he must never find it.

446
00:39:39,800 --> 00:39:40,700
All right.

447
00:39:41,100 --> 00:39:45,200
We put it away. We keep it hidden.
We never speak of it again.

448
00:39:45,600 --> 00:39:48,200
No one knows it's here, do they?

449
00:39:53,900 --> 00:39:55,000
Do they, Gandalf?

450
00:39:56,200 --> 00:39:59,400
There is one other who knew
that Bilbo had the Ring.

451
00:40:00,800 --> 00:40:03,700
I looked everywhere
for the creature Gollum.

452
00:40:04,000 --> 00:40:06,000
But the enemy found him first.

453
00:40:07,900 --> 00:40:10,300
<i>I don't know how long</i>
<i>they tortured him.</i>

454
00:40:10,600 --> 00:40:14,900
<i>But amidst the endless screams and</i>
<i>inane babble, they discerned two words:</i>

455
00:40:15,300 --> 00:40:17,300
Shire!

456
00:40:17,600 --> 00:40:19,200
Baggins!

457
00:40:19,500 --> 00:40:21,200
Shire.

458
00:40:21,500 --> 00:40:24,200
Baggins. But that would
lead them here!

459
00:40:27,100 --> 00:40:28,200
Who goes there?

460
00:40:30,000 --> 00:40:31,100
Take it, Gandalf!

461
00:40:31,500 --> 00:40:32,600
- Take it!
- No, Frodo.

462
00:40:32,800 --> 00:40:35,000
- You must take it!
- You cannot offer me this ring!

463
00:40:35,400 --> 00:40:38,500
- I'm giving it to you!
- Don't tempt me, Frodo!

464
00:40:40,200 --> 00:40:42,300
I dare not take it.

465
00:40:42,800 --> 00:40:45,100
Not even to keep it safe.

466
00:40:46,400 --> 00:40:48,300
Understand, Frodo...

467
00:40:49,100 --> 00:40:52,500
...I would use this Ring
from a desire to do good.

468
00:40:58,200 --> 00:41:03,600
But through me, it would wield a power
too great and terrible to imagine.

469
00:41:04,400 --> 00:41:07,200
- But it cannot stay in the Shire!
- No.

470
00:41:09,200 --> 00:41:10,700
No, it can't.

471
00:41:16,200 --> 00:41:17,500
What must I do?

472
00:41:19,200 --> 00:41:22,600
- You must leave. And leave quickly.
- Where? Where do I go?

473
00:41:23,000 --> 00:41:26,100
Get out of the Shire.
Make for the village of Bree.

474
00:41:26,500 --> 00:41:27,500
Bree.

475
00:41:27,800 --> 00:41:30,500
- What about you?
- I'll be waiting for you...

476
00:41:30,800 --> 00:41:33,100
...at the inn of the Prancing Pony.

477
00:41:33,400 --> 00:41:37,000
- And the Ring will be safe there?
- I don't know, Frodo.

478
00:41:37,400 --> 00:41:39,300
I don't have any answers.

479
00:41:40,900 --> 00:41:46,200
I must see the head of my order. He is
both wise and powerful. Trust me, Frodo.

480
00:41:46,600 --> 00:41:48,600
He'll know what to do.

481
00:41:49,300 --> 00:41:52,000
You'll have to leave the name
of Baggins behind you.

482
00:41:52,400 --> 00:41:54,800
That name is not safe
outside the Shire.

483
00:41:55,600 --> 00:41:58,700
Travel only by day.
And stay off the road.

484
00:41:59,600 --> 00:42:02,600
I can cut across country
easily enough.

485
00:42:05,200 --> 00:42:06,500
My dear Frodo.

486
00:42:06,900 --> 00:42:09,700
Hobbits really are amazing creatures.

487
00:42:10,100 --> 00:42:12,800
You can learn all that there is to
know about their ways in a month.

488
00:42:13,200 --> 00:42:15,400
And yet, after a hundred years...

489
00:42:15,700 --> 00:42:17,600
...they can still surprise you.

490
00:42:19,400 --> 00:42:20,700
Get down.

491
00:42:32,900 --> 00:42:36,200
Confound it all, Samwise Gamgee!
Have you been eavesdropping?

492
00:42:36,600 --> 00:42:40,900
I haven't been dropping no eaves. Honest.
I was cutting the grass under the window.

493
00:42:41,300 --> 00:42:43,600
A little late for trimming the verge,
don't you think?

494
00:42:43,900 --> 00:42:46,600
- I heard raised voices.
- What did you hear? Speak!

495
00:42:47,000 --> 00:42:48,000
Nothing important.

496
00:42:48,700 --> 00:42:52,600
That is, I heard a good deal about a ring,
a Dark Lord and the end of the world but...

497
00:42:52,900 --> 00:42:57,400
Please, Mr. Gandalf, sir, don't hurt me.
Don't turn me into anything unnatural.

498
00:42:58,400 --> 00:43:00,000
No?

499
00:43:01,200 --> 00:43:02,300
Perhaps not.

500
00:43:03,600 --> 00:43:06,900
I've thought of a better use for you.

501
00:43:08,800 --> 00:43:11,600
Come along, Samwise. Keep up.

502
00:43:13,300 --> 00:43:15,400
Be careful, both of you.

503
00:43:15,800 --> 00:43:18,400
The enemy has many spies
in his service:

504
00:43:18,800 --> 00:43:21,600
Birds, beasts.

505
00:43:23,500 --> 00:43:25,200
Is it safe?

506
00:43:26,900 --> 00:43:28,200
Never put it on...

507
00:43:28,500 --> 00:43:31,800
...for the agents of the Dark Lord
will be drawn to its power.

508
00:43:32,100 --> 00:43:33,500
Always remember, Frodo...

509
00:43:34,100 --> 00:43:37,100
...the Ring is trying to get back
to its master.

510
00:43:37,700 --> 00:43:39,700
It wants to be found.

511
00:44:20,400 --> 00:44:22,500
This is it.

512
00:44:22,900 --> 00:44:24,900
This is what?

513
00:44:25,400 --> 00:44:27,300
If I take one more step...

514
00:44:27,900 --> 00:44:31,600
...it'll be the farthest away
from home I've ever been.

515
00:44:36,100 --> 00:44:37,500
Come on, Sam.

516
00:44:46,100 --> 00:44:47,800
Remember what Bilbo used to say:

517
00:44:48,400 --> 00:44:52,000
- "It's a dangerous business, Frodo."
- <i>"Going out your door.</i>

518
00:44:52,300 --> 00:44:56,600
<i>You step onto the road,</i>
<i>and if you don't keep your feet...</i>

519
00:44:57,000 --> 00:45:01,000
<i>...there's no knowing where</i>
<i>you might be swept off to. "

520
00:45:15,000 --> 00:45:16,700
Sam.

521
00:45:20,300 --> 00:45:21,400
Wood-elves.

522
00:45:35,200 --> 00:45:38,600
They're going to the harbor
beyond the White Towers.

523
00:45:39,200 --> 00:45:40,900
To the Grey Havens.

524
00:45:41,500 --> 00:45:43,400
They're leaving Middle-earth.

525
00:45:43,800 --> 00:45:45,900
Never to return.

526
00:45:48,900 --> 00:45:50,900
I don't know why...

527
00:45:51,700 --> 00:45:53,900
...it makes me sad.

528
00:45:56,100 --> 00:46:00,600
Everywhere I lie there's a dirty
great root sticking into my back.

529
00:46:01,500 --> 00:46:03,100
Just shut your eyes...

530
00:46:03,400 --> 00:46:06,000
...and imagine you're back
in your own bed...

531
00:46:06,300 --> 00:46:10,100
...with a soft mattress
and a lovely feather pillow.

532
00:46:19,600 --> 00:46:22,200
It's not working, Mr. Frodo.

533
00:46:22,500 --> 00:46:25,200
I'm never going to be able
to sleep out here.

534
00:46:27,700 --> 00:46:29,900
Me neither, Sam.

535
00:46:58,600 --> 00:47:01,500
<i>Smoke rises</i>
<i>from the Mountain of Doom.</i>

536
00:47:01,800 --> 00:47:03,300
<i>The hour grows late.</i>

537
00:47:03,700 --> 00:47:07,100
<i>And Gandalf the Grey</i>
<i>rides to Isengard...</i>

538
00:47:07,400 --> 00:47:09,700
<i>...seeking my counsel.</i>

539
00:47:10,000 --> 00:47:13,800
For that is why you have come,
is it not?

540
00:47:14,200 --> 00:47:15,400
My old friend.

541
00:47:15,800 --> 00:47:17,300
Saruman.

542
00:47:22,200 --> 00:47:25,000
- You are sure of this?
- Beyond any doubt.

543
00:47:26,000 --> 00:47:28,200
So the Ring of Power has been found.

544
00:47:28,500 --> 00:47:31,600
All these long years,
it was in the Shire.

545
00:47:31,900 --> 00:47:34,900
- Under my very nose.
- Yet you did not have the wit to see it.

546
00:47:35,700 --> 00:47:39,900
Your love of the halfling's leaf
has clearly slowed your mind.

547
00:47:40,800 --> 00:47:44,800
But we still have time. Time enough
to counter Sauron if we act quickly.

548
00:47:45,200 --> 00:47:46,700
Time?

549
00:47:47,700 --> 00:47:50,200
What time do you think we have?

550
00:47:50,700 --> 00:47:54,400
Sauron has regained
much of his former strength.

551
00:47:54,800 --> 00:47:56,900
He cannot yet take physical form...

552
00:47:57,200 --> 00:47:59,800
...but his spirit has lost
none of its potency.

553
00:48:00,600 --> 00:48:05,400
Concealed within his fortress,
the Lord of Mordor sees all.

554
00:48:06,200 --> 00:48:11,900
His gaze pierces cloud, shadow,
earth and flesh.

555
00:48:13,600 --> 00:48:16,600
You know of what I speak, Gandalf.

556
00:48:17,700 --> 00:48:22,700
A Great Eye, lidless,
wreathed in flame.

557
00:48:24,000 --> 00:48:25,700
The Eye of Sauron.

558
00:48:25,900 --> 00:48:28,300
He is gathering all evil to him.

559
00:48:29,000 --> 00:48:30,800
Very soon, he'll have summoned
an army...

560
00:48:31,000 --> 00:48:33,600
...great enough for an assault
upon Middle-earth.

561
00:48:34,200 --> 00:48:36,400
You know this?

562
00:48:37,100 --> 00:48:38,500
How?

563
00:48:39,200 --> 00:48:40,700
I have seen it.

564
00:48:41,300 --> 00:48:44,300
A palantr is a dangerous tool,
Saruman.

565
00:48:45,100 --> 00:48:46,500
Why?

566
00:48:47,100 --> 00:48:49,700
Why should we fear to use it?

567
00:48:52,400 --> 00:48:56,200
They are not all accounted for,
the lost Seeing-stones.

568
00:48:56,600 --> 00:48:59,700
We do not know who else
may be watching.

569
00:49:02,400 --> 00:49:05,000
The hour is later than you think.

570
00:49:05,300 --> 00:49:07,500
Sauron's forces are already moving.

571
00:49:09,900 --> 00:49:12,500
The Nine have left Minas Morgul.

572
00:49:13,100 --> 00:49:14,100
The Nine?

573
00:49:14,300 --> 00:49:17,100
They crossed the River Isen
on Midsummer's Eve...

574
00:49:17,500 --> 00:49:20,000
...disguised as riders in black.

575
00:49:20,400 --> 00:49:24,200
- They've reached the Shire?
- They will find the Ring.

576
00:49:26,000 --> 00:49:28,100
And kill the one who carries it.

577
00:49:28,700 --> 00:49:30,100
Frodo!

578
00:49:42,800 --> 00:49:47,000
You did not seriously think that a Hobbit
could contend with the will of Sauron?

579
00:49:48,000 --> 00:49:50,600
There are none who can.

580
00:49:53,200 --> 00:49:55,800
Against the power of Mordor...

581
00:49:56,100 --> 00:49:58,600
...there can be no victory.

582
00:50:00,700 --> 00:50:03,800
We must join with him, Gandalf.

583
00:50:05,200 --> 00:50:07,400
We must join with Sauron.

584
00:50:10,200 --> 00:50:12,800
It would be wise, my friend.

585
00:50:13,300 --> 00:50:14,700
Tell me...

586
00:50:15,000 --> 00:50:16,000
...friend...

587
00:50:17,100 --> 00:50:21,400
...when did Saruman the Wise
abandon reason for madness?

588
00:51:01,100 --> 00:51:02,700
I gave you the chance...

589
00:51:03,900 --> 00:51:06,400
...of aiding me willingly...

590
00:51:06,800 --> 00:51:10,700
...but you have elected
the way of pain!

591
00:51:34,200 --> 00:51:35,600
Mr. Frodo?

592
00:51:36,300 --> 00:51:38,000
Frodo? Frodo!

593
00:51:39,500 --> 00:51:42,600
- I thought I'd lost you.
- What are you talking about?

594
00:51:43,000 --> 00:51:45,800
- It's just something Gandalf said.
- What did he say?

595
00:51:46,800 --> 00:51:50,500
"Don't you lose him, Samwise Gamgee."
And I don't mean to.

596
00:51:50,900 --> 00:51:54,400
Sam, we're still in the Shire.
What could possibly happen?

597
00:51:57,500 --> 00:51:58,500
Frodo.

598
00:51:58,800 --> 00:52:00,900
- Merry, it's Frodo Baggins.
- Hello, Frodo.

599
00:52:01,200 --> 00:52:02,500
Get off him.

600
00:52:03,100 --> 00:52:04,500
Come on, Frodo.

601
00:52:04,800 --> 00:52:06,600
What's the meaning of this?

602
00:52:07,200 --> 00:52:10,100
You've been into Farmer Maggot's crop!

603
00:52:11,400 --> 00:52:13,400
You get back here!

604
00:52:14,600 --> 00:52:15,800
Get out of my field!

605
00:52:16,000 --> 00:52:18,700
You'll know the devil
if I catch up with you!

606
00:52:19,100 --> 00:52:21,900
I don't know why he's so upset.
It's only a couple of carrots.

607
00:52:22,200 --> 00:52:23,200
And some cabbages.

608
00:52:23,500 --> 00:52:26,200
And those three bags of potatoes
that we lifted last week.

609
00:52:26,700 --> 00:52:30,500
- And then the mushrooms the week before.
- Yes, Pippin. My point is...

610
00:52:30,800 --> 00:52:32,900
...he's clearly overreacting.

611
00:52:33,200 --> 00:52:34,600
Run!

612
00:52:48,200 --> 00:52:50,600
Oh, that was close.

613
00:52:51,900 --> 00:52:54,800
I think I've broken something.

614
00:52:56,000 --> 00:52:58,200
Trust a Brandybuck and a Took!

615
00:52:58,600 --> 00:53:02,000
What? That was just a detour.
A short cut.

616
00:53:02,300 --> 00:53:04,500
- Short cut to what?
- Mushrooms!

617
00:53:13,400 --> 00:53:14,800
That's mine.

618
00:53:17,600 --> 00:53:19,100
That's nice, Merry.

619
00:53:19,800 --> 00:53:21,700
Here's a nice one, Sam.

620
00:53:22,000 --> 00:53:24,400
I think we should get off the road.

621
00:53:33,700 --> 00:53:35,000
Get off the road!

622
00:53:35,300 --> 00:53:36,800
Quick!

623
00:53:49,400 --> 00:53:50,900
Be quiet!

624
00:54:57,300 --> 00:54:59,300
What was that?

625
00:55:32,100 --> 00:55:33,500
Anything?

626
00:55:34,300 --> 00:55:35,700
Nothing.

627
00:55:36,500 --> 00:55:38,700
What is going on?

628
00:55:39,300 --> 00:55:43,000
That Black Rider was looking
for something. Or someone.

629
00:55:44,500 --> 00:55:45,900
Frodo?

630
00:55:46,600 --> 00:55:47,600
Get down!

631
00:56:04,700 --> 00:56:06,800
I have to leave the Shire.

632
00:56:07,900 --> 00:56:10,000
Sam and I must get to Bree.

633
00:56:10,400 --> 00:56:11,700
Right.

634
00:56:13,200 --> 00:56:15,300
Bucklebury Ferry. Follow me.

635
00:56:23,700 --> 00:56:25,000
Run!

636
00:56:26,200 --> 00:56:28,100
This way! Follow me!

637
00:56:31,900 --> 00:56:32,900
Run!

638
00:56:46,300 --> 00:56:47,900
Get the rope, Sam!

639
00:56:50,600 --> 00:56:52,000
Frodo!

640
00:56:52,800 --> 00:56:54,200
Run, Frodo!

641
00:56:54,600 --> 00:56:55,600
Go!
- Hurry!

642
00:56:55,900 --> 00:56:58,400
Frodo, come on!

643
00:56:59,400 --> 00:57:01,400
- Come on! Faster!
- Jump!

644
00:57:16,400 --> 00:57:20,400
- How far to the nearest crossing?
- The Brandywine Bridge. 20 miles.

645
00:57:35,300 --> 00:57:36,700
Come on.

646
00:57:47,900 --> 00:57:51,200
- What do you want?
- We're heading for the Prancing Pony.

647
00:57:54,900 --> 00:57:57,600
Hobbits. Four Hobbits!

648
00:57:57,900 --> 00:58:01,700
What's more, out of the Shire by your
talk. What business brings you to Bree?

649
00:58:02,400 --> 00:58:05,300
We wish to stay at the inn.
Our business is our own.

650
00:58:06,500 --> 00:58:08,900
All right, young sir.
I meant no offense.

651
00:58:09,300 --> 00:58:11,700
It's my job to ask questions
after nightfall.

652
00:58:12,000 --> 00:58:14,700
There's talk of strange folk abroad.

653
00:58:15,100 --> 00:58:17,100
Can't be too careful.

654
00:58:36,900 --> 00:58:40,300
Out of the way!
Watch where you're walking.

655
00:59:04,400 --> 00:59:06,000
Excuse me.

656
00:59:07,100 --> 00:59:09,700
Good evening, little masters.
What can I do for you?

657
00:59:10,000 --> 00:59:15,800
If you're seeking accommodation, we got
some cozy Hobbit-sized rooms available.

658
00:59:16,400 --> 00:59:20,800
Always proud to cater
to the Little Folk, Mister?

659
00:59:22,100 --> 00:59:24,000
Underhill. My name's Underhill.

660
00:59:25,400 --> 00:59:27,800
- Underhill, yes.
- We're friends of Gandalf the Grey.

661
00:59:28,100 --> 00:59:31,200
- Can you tell him we've arrived?
- Gandalf?

662
00:59:31,700 --> 00:59:33,300
Gandalf.

663
00:59:34,200 --> 00:59:35,800
Oh, yes...

664
00:59:36,200 --> 00:59:38,100
...I remember. Elderly chap.

665
00:59:38,600 --> 00:59:41,400
Big grey beard, pointy hat.

666
00:59:41,900 --> 00:59:43,600
Not seen him for six months.

667
00:59:50,600 --> 00:59:51,800
What do we do now?

668
00:59:59,000 --> 01:00:00,200
Sam...

669
01:00:00,500 --> 01:00:02,300
...he'll be here. He'll come.

670
01:00:05,100 --> 01:00:07,100
Get out of my way!

671
01:00:09,600 --> 01:00:11,200
What's that?

672
01:00:11,400 --> 01:00:13,800
This, my friend, is a pint.

673
01:00:14,200 --> 01:00:15,700
It comes in pints?

674
01:00:16,100 --> 01:00:19,700
- I'm getting one.
- You got a whole half already!

675
01:00:26,200 --> 01:00:29,800
That fellow's done nothing
but stare at you since we arrived.

676
01:00:33,500 --> 01:00:35,000
Excuse me.

677
01:00:36,900 --> 01:00:39,800
That Man in the corner. Who is he?

678
01:00:41,000 --> 01:00:45,200
He's one of them Rangers. They're
dangerous folk, wandering the Wilds.

679
01:00:45,700 --> 01:00:50,000
What his right name is, I've never heard,
but around here he's known as Strider.

680
01:00:52,600 --> 01:00:53,700
Strider.

681
01:01:06,900 --> 01:01:09,900
<i>Baggins.</i>

682
01:01:13,600 --> 01:01:15,000
<i>Baggins.</i>

683
01:01:27,400 --> 01:01:29,500
Baggins? Sure, I know a Baggins.

684
01:01:30,500 --> 01:01:33,200
He's over there. Frodo Baggins.

685
01:01:33,500 --> 01:01:36,400
He's my second cousin,
once removed on his mother's side...

686
01:01:36,700 --> 01:01:38,900
...and my third cousin, twice removed...

687
01:01:43,500 --> 01:01:45,200
- Pippin!
- Steady on, Frodo.

688
01:02:14,900 --> 01:02:17,200
You cannot hide.

689
01:02:20,300 --> 01:02:23,200
I see you.

690
01:02:25,100 --> 01:02:27,700
There is no life...

691
01:02:28,000 --> 01:02:30,000
...in the void.

692
01:02:30,300 --> 01:02:31,800
Only...

693
01:02:32,800 --> 01:02:34,200
...death.

694
01:02:40,300 --> 01:02:44,900
You draw far too much attention
to yourself, "Mr. Underhill."

695
01:02:49,800 --> 01:02:50,800
What do you want?

696
01:02:51,100 --> 01:02:53,000
A little more caution from you.
That is no trinket you carry.

697
01:02:53,500 --> 01:02:56,400
- I carry nothing.
- Indeed.

698
01:02:56,800 --> 01:02:59,200
I can avoid being seen if I wish...

699
01:02:59,500 --> 01:03:03,000
...but to disappear entirely,
that is a rare gift.

700
01:03:03,700 --> 01:03:06,200
- Who are you?
- Are you frightened?

701
01:03:07,500 --> 01:03:08,500
Yes.

702
01:03:08,800 --> 01:03:12,500
Not nearly frightened enough.
I know what hunts you.

703
01:03:16,700 --> 01:03:19,100
Let him go!
Or I'll have you, Longshanks.

704
01:03:20,900 --> 01:03:24,800
You have a stout heart, little Hobbit.
But that will not save you.

705
01:03:25,100 --> 01:03:27,900
You can no longer wait
for the wizard, Frodo.

706
01:03:28,300 --> 01:03:29,400
They're coming.

707
01:04:52,900 --> 01:04:54,400
What are they?

708
01:04:56,700 --> 01:04:58,700
They were once Men.

709
01:04:59,000 --> 01:05:01,100
Great kings of Men.

710
01:05:01,700 --> 01:05:04,700
Then Sauron the Deceiver gave to them
nine rings of power.

711
01:05:05,400 --> 01:05:08,400
Blinded by their greed,
they took them without question.

712
01:05:08,800 --> 01:05:11,900
One by one, falling into darkness.

713
01:05:12,300 --> 01:05:14,600
Now they are slaves to his will.

714
01:05:17,100 --> 01:05:18,800
They are the NazgI.

715
01:05:19,100 --> 01:05:21,700
Ringwraiths. Neither living nor dead.

716
01:05:22,500 --> 01:05:23,800
At all times they feel...

717
01:05:24,200 --> 01:05:26,000
<i>...the presence of the Ring...</i>

718
01:05:26,300 --> 01:05:30,600
<i>...drawn to the power of the One.</i>
<i>They will never stop hunting you.</i>

719
01:05:40,800 --> 01:05:43,600
- Where are you taking us?
- Into the Wild.

720
01:05:51,900 --> 01:05:55,800
How do we know this Strider
is a friend of Gandalf?

721
01:05:56,200 --> 01:05:58,900
I think a servant of the enemy
would look fairer...

722
01:05:59,400 --> 01:06:03,100
...and feel fouler.
- He's foul enough.

723
01:06:03,900 --> 01:06:06,600
We have no choice but to trust him.

724
01:06:07,000 --> 01:06:10,300
- But where is he leading us?
- To Rivendell, Master Gamgee.

725
01:06:12,800 --> 01:06:15,900
- To the house of Elrond.
- Did you hear that? Rivendell.

726
01:06:16,700 --> 01:06:19,300
We're going to see the Elves.

727
01:06:41,000 --> 01:06:45,000
- Gentlemen, we do not stop till nightfall.
- What about breakfast?

728
01:06:45,400 --> 01:06:48,000
- You've already had it.
- We've had one, yes.

729
01:06:48,300 --> 01:06:50,400
What about second breakfast?

730
01:06:54,000 --> 01:06:57,000
Don't think he knows
about second breakfast, Pip.

731
01:06:57,300 --> 01:07:02,300
What about elevenses? Luncheon?
